==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Madrigal
<hw>Mad"ri*gal</hw> <pr>(m⟦acr⟧d"r⟦icr⟧*g⟦ait⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[It. <ets>madrigale</ets>, OIt. <ets>madriale</ets>,
<ets>mandriale</ets> (cf. LL. <ets>matriale</ets>); of uncertain origin,
possibly fr. It <ets>mandra</ets> flock, L. <ets>mandra</ets> stall,
herd of cattle, Gr. <grk>ma`ndra</grk> fold, stable; hence,
<ets>madrigal</ets>, originally, a pastoral song.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A little amorous poem, sometimes called a <altname>pastoral
poem</altname>, containing some tender and delicate, though simple,
thought.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose artful strains have oft delayed⟦br⟧
The huddling brook to hear his <qex>madrigal</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>An unaccompanied polyphonic song,
in four, five, or more parts, set to secular words, but full of
counterpoint and imitation, and adhering to the old church modes. Unlike
the freer glee, it is best sung with several voices on a part. See
<er>Glee</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madrigaler</ent>⟦br⟧
